[1] Cholera - Uganda (Kibaale)
Date: Thu, 4 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: African News Dimension [edited]
<http://www.andnetwork.com/index?service=direct/0/Home/recent.titleStory&sp=l124267>

Two people are confirmed to have died of cholera in Kitebere and Sangalawo
fishing villages on Lake Albert in Ndaiga parish, Mpeefu Sub-County,
Kibaale district of western Uganda. According to the District Director of
Health Services in Kibaale, Dr. Dan Kyamanywa, other 28 people have also
been admitted at Kasojo health center IV where they have been treated since
the onset of cholera on 18 Dec 2006.
Dr. Kyamanywa attributes the cholera outbreak to sanitary practices and
poor hygiene around the lakeshores of Lake Albert. He advises the people
living at the fishing villages and other adjacent areas to stop eating
foods being sold at road side because they are contaminated.
The fishing villages of Lake Albert are prone to cholera outbreaks annually
due to lack of properly located latrines and the absence of clean safe
drinking water.
[Byline: Ronald Tumusiime]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Uganda showing Kibaale in western Uganda bordering Lake Albert
can be found at:
